"'''Roar'''" is a song by American recording artist [[Katy Perry]] for her fourth [[studio album]], ''[[Prism (Katy Perry album)|Prism]]'' (2013). It was serviced to radio stations as the [[lead single]] from the record on August 10, 2013; it was digitally released on August 12, 2013. The song was written and produced by [[Dr. Luke]], [[Max Martin]], and [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]], with additional songwriting provided by Perry and [[Bonnie McKee]]. The lyrics address standing up for oneself and self-empowerment.

"Roar" received generally mixed reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]; many appreciated its overall production, while others felt that its lyrical content contained "clich<U+00E9>s". The song became Perry's eighth non-consecutive number one song on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and, also peaked at number one in various charts, including Australia, Canada, Ireland, Scotland, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom. Additionally, it also reached the top five in most international charts, including France, Germany, Italy, and Switzerland.

To promote the song, Perry performed at the [[2013 MTV Video Music Awards]], under the [[Brooklyn Bridge]], as the ceremony's closing, on ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor]]'', and on the German TV show ''[[Schlag den Raab]]''. Grady Hall and Mark Kudsi directed the song's music video, which features Perry trying to adapt to the jungle where she survived a plane crash, and taming a tiger. It garnered generally mixed reviews from music critics. "Roar" was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and for the [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]]. The song is among some of the [[List of best-selling singles worldwide|best-selling singles worldwide]].

==Background and composition==
{{listen
 | pos          = right
 | filename     = Katy Perry - Roar.ogg
 | title        = Katy Perry <U+2014> "Roar" (2013)
 | description  = A 23 second sample of "Roar", a [[power pop]] song with influences of rock sub-genres that lyrically, revolves around a theme of empowerment.
 | format       = [[Ogg]]
}}
The song was mixed by [[Serban Ghenea]] at MixStar Studios. "Roar" was recorded in four other studios: Luke's in the Boo, Playback Recording Studio and Secret Garden Studios, all located in the state of [[California]], as well as MXM Studios in [[Stockholm, Sweden]].<ref name="Notes">{{Cite album-notes |title=Prism |albumlink=Prism (Katy Perry album) |artist=Katy Perry |year=2013 |format=liner notes |publisher=[[Capitol Records]] |location=United States}}</ref> All its development took place in March 2013.<ref name=KatyOnPrism>{{cite web|last=Perry|first=Katy|title=Katy Perry - Prism|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dCIVlrUWMn8|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=November 4, 2013}}</ref> During an interview with [[MTV]], McKee described "Roar" as "kind of a 'pick yourself up and dust yourself off and keep going', female-empowerment song" and "kind of an epiphany song."<ref>{{cite web|author=Vena, Jocelyn|title=Go Behind Katy Perry's 'Raw And Emotional' Prism Writing Sessions|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1716064/katy-perry-bonnie-mckee-prism.jhtml|work=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom]]|accessdate=December 23, 2013|date=October 23, 2013}}</ref> Perry said she wrote the song after undergoing therapy, saying she was "sick of keeping all these feelings inside and not speaking up for myself".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/katy-perry-new-song-called-2154555 |title=Katy Perry new song called Roar |publisher=Mirror.co.uk |date= |accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref>

The song's release was announced with the release of a video teaser, entitled "Burning Baby Blue", that saw Perry burning a blue wig.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry sets fire to blue wig in symbolic Roar teaser|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/08/02/katy-perry-sets-fire-to-blue-wig-in-symbolic-roar-teaser-3909718/|work=Metro|publisher=[[DMG Media]]|accessdate=December 1, 2013|date=August 2, 2013}}</ref> More video teasers were released onto [[YouTube]], that showed Perry at a funeral with a coffin decorated with the singer's famous pink and white pinwheels dress,<ref name="bill">{{cite web|date=August 6, 2013|accessdate=December 1, 2013|title=Katy Perry Buries Alter-Ego In New Teaser Clip|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/katy-perry/387796-katy-perry-roar-second-teaser-the-third-coming-prism#3ChMSJcTbyzet0i0.99|website=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom]]}}</ref>  and entering a recording booth while dressed with a "throwback" jacket featured in the single's cover art,<ref name="Williott">{{cite web|last=Williott|first=Carl|title=Katy Perry Rocks "Roar" Jacket In Latest Teaser: Hear Another Snippet Of The Song|url=http://www.idolator.com/7476606/katy-perry-roar-teaser-snippet-jacket|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|publisher=[[Spin Media]]|date=August 9, 2013|accessdate=December 1, 2013}}</ref> which was revealed on August 8, 2013.<ref name="Williott"/> It features a tiger print border around Perry, who wears a blue [[Japan]]ese silk sukajan jacket, with the image of a tiger printed on its back.<ref name="style">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' Single Cover Style Is Very Lisa Frank Meets 'Drive'|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/08/08/katy-perry-roar-cover/last=Keirans|first=Maeve|website=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom]]|accessdate=August 8, 2013|date=August 8, 2013}}</ref> On the same day of the song's digital release, a lyric video for it, produced by Joe Humpay, [[Aya Tanimura]], Tim Zimmer, and Tuan Le, was released onto YouTube. It primarily shows Perry doing daily activities such as eating breakfast, going to the bathroom, and taking a bath, while texting the lyrics of "Roar" to friends. Some words are substituted with various [[Emoji]] characters.<ref name="Video">{{cite web|last=Moraski |first=Lauren |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57598116/watch-katy-perrys-emoticon-lyric-video-for-roar/ |title=Watch: Katy Perry's emoticon lyric video for "Roar" |publisher=''CBS News'' |date=August 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mallenbaum|first=Carly|title=Katy Perry releases 'emoticon' video for 'Roar'|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/08/12/katy-perry-roar-emoticon/2642249/|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|accessdate=August 12, 2013|date=August 12, 2013}}</ref> It was target of plagiarism accusations by music producer [[Dillon Francis]], who felt it copied the concept of instant messaging from his video entitled "Messages".<ref name="Copy">{{cite web|last=Reilly|first=Dan|title=Dillon Francis Says Katy Perry's 'Roar' Ripped Him Off, But She'll Play the VMAs Anyway|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/katy-perry-rip-off-dillon-francis-roar-video-vmas/|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=August 12, 2013|date=August 12, 2013}}</ref>

Musically, "Roar" is styled in [[power pop]], and features elements of [[glam rock]] and [[arena rock]].<ref name="Idolator1">{{cite web |url=http://idolator.com/6637662/katy-perry-roar-leak |title=Katy Perry's "Roar" Leaks: Listen To The Foot-Stomping 'Prism' Anthem |first=Robbie |last=Daw |work=''[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]'' |publisher=Buzz Media |date=August 10, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref><ref name="MTV1">{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1712137/katy-perry-roar-teaser-satin-cape.jhtml |title=Katy Perry Mugs Like A 'Champion' In New 'Roar' Teaser: Watch! |first=Christina |last=Garibaldi |work=[[MTV News]] |publisher= [[Viacom Media Networks]]|date=August 9, 2013 |accessdate=August 10, 2013 }}</ref><ref name="Gigwise">{{cite web |url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/83475/new-katy-perry-single-roar-is-perfect---say-katy-perry-fans |title=New Katy Perry single 'Roar' is 'perfect' |first=Andrew |last=Tendell |work=[[Gigwise]] |publisher=Giant Digital |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref><ref name="Slate1">{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/08/12/katy_perry_new_single_roar_latest_song_is_a_jock_jams_pastiche.html |title=Katy Perry new single "Roar": Latest song is a Jock Jams pastiche |first=Forrest |last=Wickman |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |publisher=[[The Washington Post Company]] |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013 }}</ref> Throughout the song, Perry "flexes diva-like vocals", singing the lyric "Hey!" several times in a way resemblant of [[The Lumineers]].<ref name="rollingstone1">{{cite web|author=Ganz, Caryn|title=Katy Perry - "Roar"|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/songreviews/roar-20130828|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=Wenner Media|accessdate=December 23, 2013|date=August 28, 2013}}</ref> The song's [[instrumentation]] is composed of "pounding" pianos and "booming" bass drums.<ref name="rollingstone1"/> According to the sheet music published by [[Alfred Publishing|Alfred Publishing Co., Inc]]. on Musicnotes.com, "Roar" is composed in the key of [[B-flat major|B{{music|flat}} major]] and set in a [[Common time|4/4]] [[time signature]] at a moderate [[tempo]] of 90 [[beats per minute]]. The melody spans the tonal range of B{{music|flat}}<sub>3</sub> to D<sub>5</sub>, while the music follows the [[chord progression]] of B{{music|flat}}<U+2013>Cm<U+2013>Gm<U+2013>E{{music|flat}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry "Roar" Sheet Music - Download & Print|url=http://m.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0122655&ref=google&utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=Alfred Publishing Co. Inc|accessdate=December 23, 2013}}</ref> The song shares the theme of empowerment with Perry's hit single "[[Firework (Katy Perry song)|Firework]]".<ref name="Vibe">{{cite web|last=Rogulewski|first=Charley|title=Katy Perry's New Single "Roar" Leaks|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/katy-perry-roar|publisher=Vibe magazine|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name="EnterntainmentWeeklyReview">{{cite web|last=Atkinson|first=Katie|title=Katy Perry is back with a 'Roar' <U+2014> hear her new single now|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/08/11/katy-perry-roar-single-listen/|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=August 11, 2013}}</ref> Perry described the track as a song speaking about standing up for oneself.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713155/katy-perry-roar-biggest-bully.jhtml|first= Christina|last= Garibaldi|publisher= MTV.com|title= Katy Perry Used To Be Her 'Biggest Bully' Before 'Roar'|date= August 27, 2013}}</ref>

==Critical reception==
Miriam Coleman from ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' appreciated the songs's "easy poppy beat" and the its "repeated refrains", factors which the reviewer believed that contributed to make the song a "determined note for the new album".<ref name="RollingStone2">{{cite web|last=Coleman|first=Miriam|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/katy-perry-drops-new-song-roar-20130811 |title=Katy Perry Drops New Song, 'Roar' |publisher=''Rolling Stone''|date=August 11, 2013}}</ref> James Montgomery of [[MTV]] described it as "one of the more perfect pop songs to come down the pipeline in quite a while". Gerrick D. Kennedy from ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' also gave a positive review, classifying "Roar" as a "sweet, poppy confection with a bit of bite".<ref name="Angeles">{{cite news|last=Kennedy |first=Gerrick D. |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-to-katy-perry-roar-20130811,0,3722661.story |title=Listen to Katy Perry's new single 'Roar' |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=August 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name="MTV2">{{cite web|last=Montgomery|first=James|title=Katy Perry's 'Roar:' The Power Of Positive Thinking|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1712162/katy-perry-roar-release.jhtml|work=MTV News|publisher=Viacom Media Network|accessdate=August 12, 2013|date=August 12, 2013}}</ref> Melinda Newman from [[HitFix]] saw the song as a "change of pace" for Perry,<ref>{{cite web|last=Newman |first=Melinda |url=http://www.hitfix.com/news/katy-perrys-new-single-roar-in-full-is-a-fierce-fun-anthem-listen |title=Listen: Katy Perry's new single Roar in full, is a fierce, fun anthem |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=June 25, 2013 |accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> whilst Andrew Hampp from ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' believed it to be a return to the style of her album ''[[One of the Boys (Katy Perry album)|One of the Boys]]'', but criticized its tempo and its lyrics that "rarely rise above easy clich<U+00E9>s and rhymes".<ref name="Track">{{cite web|last=Hampp |first=Andrew |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/5645969/katy-perry-roar-track-review |title=Katy Perry, 'Roar: Track Review |publisher=''Billboard''. [[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=August 12, 2013|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> Bill Lamb from [[About.com]] gave "Roar" an extremely positive review, describing it as a "slice of uplifting, personal pop that is instantly catchy and memorable". He also highlighted the "confident" lyrics and the "bouncy feel" of the music.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lamb, Bill|title=Katy Perry - "Roar"|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/Katy-Perry-roar.htm|work=[[About.com]]|accessdate=December 25, 2013}}</ref> A reviewer from Lava Lizard found the song to be "predictable", while Sal Cinquemani from [[Slant Magazine]] described the song as "more of a yelp than a roar".<ref name="Lava Lizard">{{cite web|title=New Song: Katy Perry <U+2013> "Roar"|url=http://thelavalizard.com/2013/08/new-song-katy-perry-roar/|publisher=Lava Lizard|accessdate=August 10, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Slant">{{cite web|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|title=Listen to Katy Perry's "Roar"|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/10/listen-to-katy-perrys-roar|publisher=Slant Magazine|accessdate=August 10, 2013}}</ref>

==Usage in sports==
On September 16, 2013, the song was unexpectedly used during player introductions by the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] in their home opener against the [[Bengals<U+2013>Steelers rivalry|rival]] [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] on [[Monday Night Football]], to tie in the song's [[jungle]] theme with the [[Bengal tiger|team's nickname]]. Throughout the game, the song was also played sporadically during game breaks. Although the Bengals won the game 20-10, the song drew much criticism by Bengals fans and even some of the team's players. One Bengals fan even told the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' that [[Steeler Nation|Steeler fans]] sitting near him were laughing at the Bengals fans throughout the game; the Steelers themselves have used the [[Styx (band)|Styx]] song "[[Renegade (Styx song)|Renegade]]" frequently at [[Heinz Field]] since 2001.<ref name=steelers>{{Cite news | title = Steelers Turn To Power Of 'Renegade' To Fuel Defense: 'Oh Momma' Rallying Cry For Black And Gold| newspaper = [[WTAE-TV]]| publisher = www.thepittsburghchannel.com| date = November 9, 2009 | url = http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/sports/21562637/detail.html|archivedate=November 22, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5lUNrH0FM}}</ref> Four days after the game, the team publicly apologized, announcing that while the song would not be nixed from [[Paul Brown Stadium]]'s playlist completely, the team would use a [[hard rock]] or [[classic rock]] song for player introductions moving forward.<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry song nixed for intros|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/9701089/cincinnati-bengals-tone-katy-perry-roar-fan-backlash Katy Perry song nixed for intros|publisher=ESPN|date=September 21, 2013}}</ref>

==Plagiarism accusations==
Upon the release of "Roar", many accused Perry of copying [[Sara Bareilles]]' "[[Brave (Sara Bareilles song)|Brave]]".<ref name="Angeles"/><ref name="MusicMix">{{cite web|last=Anderson |first=Kyle |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2013/08/12/katy-perry-roar-sara-bareilles-brave/ |title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' sounds an awful lot like Sara Bareilles' 'Brave', says the Internet |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=August 12, 2013 |accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Brave-ly Roar">{{cite web|last=Pavlova|first=Victoria|title=Katy Perry And Sara Bareilles "Brave"-ly "Roar" In The Face Of Plagiarism Speculation|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/article/katy-perry-roar-sara-bareilles-brave-similarity_3810877|publisher=Contactmusic.com|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Global News">{{cite web|last=Kennedy|first=John R.|title=Katy Perry accused of being copy cat|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/778353/katy-perry-accused-of-being-copy-cat/|publisher=Global News|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> When Bareilles herself was asked about the controversy between the two songs, she responded: "Katy's a friend of mine and we've known each other a really long time", and was upset that there was a "negative spin on two artists that are choosing to share positive messages." She also mentioned she had known about "Roar" before its release and stated "If I'm not mad I don't know why anybody else is upset".<ref name="Bareilles ABC">{{cite web|title=Sara Bareilles on 'Brave' vs. Katy Perry's 'Roar'|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/08/sara-bareilles-on-brave-vs-katy-perrys-roar/|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=August 29, 2013}}</ref> In response to the accusations, [[Dr. Luke]] tweeted on August 14, 2013: "Roar was written and recorded before Brave came out."<ref>{{cite web|title=too bad .....|url=https://twitter.com/TheDoctorLuke/statuses/367577095125204993|publisher="[[Twitter]]"|accessdate=September 14, 2013|date=August 14, 2013}}</ref> In direct response to the attention "Brave" received as a result of the plagiarism accusations, Bareilles' record label, [[Epic Records]], decided to promote "Brave" to the [[Contemporary hit radio|mainstream pop]] [[radio format]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|title=Weekly Chart Notes: The 27 Songs To Spend At Least 10 Weeks Atop The Hot 100|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5657724/weekly-chart-notes-the-27-songs-to-spend-at-least-10-weeks-atop-the-hot-100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=August 16, 2013|accessdate=August 30, 2013}}</ref>

==Commercial performance==

===North America===
On the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], the song debuted at number eighty-five on the week-ending August 24, 2013 due to radio airplay.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5650672/robin-thicke-leads-hot-100-for-10th-week-katy-perrys-roar-debuts|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|title=Robin Thicke Leads Hot 100 For 10th Week, Katy Perry's 'Roar' Debuts|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=August 14, 2013|accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref> The following week, during its first week on sale, "Roar" sold 557,000 digital copies, thus earning Perry the highest first-week sales numbers of 2013 and also her biggest digital song sales week ever, breaking her previous record held by "[[Firework (song)|Firework]]", which sold 509,000 digital copies for the week ending January 8, 2011.<ref name="roar">{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=Luke Bryan Nets No. 1 Album, Katy Perry's 'Roar' Tops Digital Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5659205/luke-bryan-nets-no-1-album-katy-perrys-roar-tops-digital-songs|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=August 21, 2013|accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref> The song soared eighty-three positions to number two in its second week, kept from the top spot by only [[Robin Thicke]]'s "[[Blurred Lines]]", while becoming Perry's twelfth top-ten hit single in the United States, and her ninth consecutive single to peak within the top three on the Hot 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5660927/robin-thicke-no-1-katy-perry-no-2-on-hot-100|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|title=Robin Thicke No. 1, Katy Perry No. 2 On Hot 100|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=August 21, 2013}}</ref> After another week at number two, "Roar" reached number one for the chart dated September 14, 2013, becoming Perry's eighth number one on the Hot 100 and her ninth [[Hot Digital Songs|digital number-one single]], after selling 448,000 copies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5680131/katy-perry-dethrones-robin-thicke-atop-hot-100|work=Billboard|title=Katy Perry Dethrones Robin Thicke Atop Hot 100|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=September 4, 2013|accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> "Roar" spent a total two weeks at number one before it was surpassed by [[Miley Cyrus]]' "[[Wrecking Ball (Miley Cyrus song)|Wrecking Ball]]".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695590/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-swings-to-top-of-hot-100|work=Billboard|title=Miley Cyrus' 'Wrecking Ball' Swings Atop Hot 100|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=September 18, 2013}}</ref> On its seventh frame, the song moved 2-1 (peak audience impressions of 159 million) and became Perry's sixth number one on the [[Hot 100 Airplay]], as well as becoming the singer's fastest climbing to the top position.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5733088/miley-cyrus-wrecking-ball-spends-second-week-atop-hot-100|title=Miley Cyrus' 'Wrecking Ball' Spends Second Week Atop Hot 100|date=September 25, 2013}}</ref>

"Roar" also reached number one on both the US [[Pop Songs]] and [[Adult Pop Songs]]. The number-one position on the ''Pop Songs'' chart gave Perry her tenth number one, tying her with [[Rihanna]] for the most number ones on the airplay-based chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5695476/katy-perry-ties-for-most-pop-songs-no-1s |title=Katy Perry Ties For Most Pop Songs No. 1s|accessdate=September 16, 2013}}</ref> The number-one position on the ''Adult Pop Songs'' chart also gave Perry multiple milestones; it became her eighth chart topper, tying her with [[Maroon 5]] and [[Pink (singer)|P!nk]] as the act with the most number-ones there. It also made the fastest ascension to the top spot; a record previously held by Perry's own single "[[California Gurls]]" (2010).<ref name="Britney"/> It also set airplay records in both of the charts, by becoming the most weekly-played song in history, with 16,065 and 5,309 plays per week, respectively.<ref name=BillboardPDF>{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary|title=Miley Cyrus, Paramore Reach Top 10; Lorde Leaps To History|url=http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/TFMm1007.pdf|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> 

The song has also reached the top spot on both the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult contemporary chart]] and [[Hot Dance Club Songs]].<ref name="Britney">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5719511/chart-highlights-britney-spears-bows-katy-perry-lady-gaga-leap-to-no-1|title=Britney Spears Bows, Katy Perry, Lady Gaga Leap To No. 1|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/TFMm0923.pdf|title=Spears<U+2019> <U+2018>Work<U+2019> Is Just Beginning; Perry, Drake Score New No. 1s|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=September 23, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/code/5762990/diplo-paris-hilton-lady-gaga-debut-on-dance-charts|title=Diplo, Paris Hilton, Lady Gaga Debut On Dance Charts|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=billboard.com|date=October 17, 2013}}</ref> In addition to this, the track also reached number one on both the [[On-Demand Songs|On Demand]] and [[Streaming Songs|Streaming]] charts, with a weekly peak of 2.1 million and 12 million, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5680131/katy-perry-dethrones-robin-thicke-atop-hot-100|title=Katy Perry Dethrones Robin Thicke Atop Hot 10 |publisher=Billboard.com |accessdate=December 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name="streaming">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5687387/katy-perrys-roar-rules-hot-100-for-second-week-lorde-reaches-top-3|work=Billboard|title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' Rules Hot 100 For Second Week, Lorde Reaches Top 3|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=September 11, 2013}}</ref> "Roar" surpassed digital sales of four million in its seventeenth week, faster than any other song in digital history. Its sales reached 4.41 million by the end of 2013, becoming the sixth best-seller of the year. Perry has seven of her songs with sales more than four million, the most for any artist.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grein|first=Paul|title=Chart Watch: "The Monster" Lives Up To Its Title|url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/music-news/chart-watch-monster-lives-title-013939655.html|publisher=Yahoo|accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name="sales 2013">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5855151/justin-timberlakes-2020-2013s-best-selling-album-blurred-lines-top-song|title=Justin Timberlake's '20/20' 2013's Best Selling Album, 'Blurred Lines' Top Song |first=Keith |last=Caulfield |work=Billboard Magazine |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=January 2, 2014 |accessdate=January 2, 2014 }}</ref> By February 2014, "Roar" had surpassed five million sales, and was Perry's fifth song to reach that level. Perry is the only artist to have five quintuple million sellers.<ref name=sales>{{cite web|last=Grein|first=Paul|url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/music-news/chart-watch-bet-pharrell-happy-221341644.html |title=Chart Watch: You Bet Pharrell Is "Happy" |work=Yahoo Music|date=February 26, 2014|accessdate=February 26, 2014}}</ref>

On August 31, 2013, "Roar" debuted at number one on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] on the strength of digital downloads.<ref name="canada">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-08-31/canadian-hot-100|title=Canadian Hot 100: August 31, 2013|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=August 31, 2013|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> In doing so, it became only the eleventh song to debut at the peak position on the chart, and it also became Perry's third number-one debut, making her the artist with the most number one debuts on the chart.<ref name="canada" /> It also became Perry's ninth Canadian number one, breaking the tie she shared with Rihanna for the most chart toppers in the country. It has so far spent five non-consecutive weeks atop the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2013-10-05/canadian-hot-100|title=Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media |date=October 5, 2013|accessdate=September 26, 2013}}</ref> "Roar" was also in the top of the [[List of number-one digital songs of 2013 (Canada)|Canadian Digital Chart]] for three non-consecutive weeks; there, it was Perry's sixth number-one single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/Top20Digital.aspx?scid=65122|title=Digital Tracks |work=Music Canada|publisher=Nielsen SoundScan Charts |date=September 11, 2013|accessdate=September 15, 2013}}</ref> In Mexico, it reached number one on the [[Monitor Latino]] English-language airplay chart.<ref name="RadioNotas">{{cite web|url=http://monitorlatino.com.mx//Charts/Ingles93020131062013.html|work = [[Monitor Latino]]|publisher=RadioNotas|accessdate=October 6, 2013|title=Top 20 Ingles: Del 30 de Septiembre al 6 de Octubre del 2013}}</ref>

===Elsewhere===
In the United Kingdom, "Roar" entered at number one on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on September 8, 2013, selling 179,500 copies in its first week and ending the prolonged number-one run of [[Ellie Goulding]]'s "[[Burn (Ellie Goulding song)|Burn]]". The song became Perry's fourth UK number-one single.<ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/katy-perry-roars-to-the-top-of-the-official-singles-chart-2475/ |title=Katy Perry Roars to the top of the Official Singles Chart |publisher=Officialcharts.com |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> The single spent two weeks atop the chart before being succeeded by "[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]" by [[Jason Derulo]] ft. [[2 Chainz]]. The song also debuted atop the adjacent UK chart of Scotland and the [[Irish Recorded Music Association|Irish Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2013&year=2013&week=34 |title=GFK Chart-Track |publisher=Chart-track.co.uk |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/22/2013-09-14/ |title=2013-09-14 Top 40 Scottish Singles Archive |publisher=Official Charts |date=September 14, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> It has been certified Platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]], denoting sales of over 600,000 copies in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=Certified Awards |publisher=Bpi.co.uk |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> "Roar" was the 6th best-selling song of 2013 in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-selling-singles-of-2013-so-far-2523/ |title=The Official Top 40 Biggest Selling Singles Of 2013 So Far! |publisher=Officialcharts.com |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref>

The song reached number four on the [[FIMI|Italian Singles Chart]], where it was eventually certified [[Music certification|Gold]] by the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]], for sales of over 15,000 digital copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fimi.it/archivio_certificazioni.php |title=FIMI - Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana - Certificazioni |publisher=Fimi.it |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> In Spain, the single peaked at number five on the sales chart, according to [[PROMUSICAE]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://www.spanishcharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=spanishcharts.com |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> In Austria, it became a number-one on the [[<U+00D6>3 Austria Top 40]], while in Germany and Switzerland it reached numbers two and three, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charts.de/song.asp?artist=Katy+Perry&title=Roar&cat=s&country=de |title=charts.de |publisher=charts.de |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://www.swisscharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=swisscharts.com |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> In the Belgian [[Ultratop 50]], "Roar" peaked at number five in [[Flanders]] and number seven in [[Wallonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=ultratop.be |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=ultratop.be |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> In France the song peaked at number six.<ref>{{cite web|author=Steffen Hung |url=http://www.lescharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Katy+Perry&titel=Roar&cat=s |title=Katy Perry - Roar |publisher=lescharts.com |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> The single also reached the top five in Norway.<ref name="Norwegian singles chart">{{cite web|url=http://lista.vg.no/liste/topp-20-single/1/dato/2013/uke/36|title=Norwegian singles chart|date=September 6, 2013|accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref> "Roar" found placings among the top-ten of the airplay charts in Bulgaria, Croatia, Czech Republic, Hungary, and Slovakia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bamp-bg.org/2009-07-08-09-48-53/nielsen/423-09092013-15092013.html|publisher=Bulgarian Association of the Music Producers|language=Bulgarian|archiveurl=http://archive.is/OoJtZ|archivedate=September 17, 2013|title=09.09.2013-19.08.2013 - Airplay Top 5}}</ref><ref name="croatian">{{cite web|url=http://radio.hrt.hr/data/files/3db3ae1f9cfaf7b47fcf14a2b995b9eafe246a5c.xls|title=ARC, Issue Date: September 9, 2013|publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision|HRT]] |date=September 9, 2013|accessdate=September 9, 2012|language=Croatian}}</ref> Within the unofficial digital charts of Greece, Luxembourg and Portugal, compiled outside of the respective countries by ''Billboard'', "Roar" peaked at number two in both the Greece and Luxembourg charts and at number eight in the Portuguese chart.<ref name="billboard.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-08-31/greece|work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=June 13, 2013|title=Greece Digital Songs - August 31, 2013 }}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-09-28/luxembourg-digital-songs|work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=September 21, 2013|title=Luxembourg Digital Songs - September 28, 2013 }}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2013-08-24/portugal|work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=August 24, 2013|title=Portugal Digital Songs - August 24, 2013 }}{{subscription required}}</ref>

"Roar" entered at the top of the [[New Zealand Singles Chart]] after just four days on sale, becoming Perry's ninth number-one single, second top debut and her eleventh top ten.<ref name="Music NZ">{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2256|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=August 16, 2013|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart - 19 August 2013|archiveurl=http://archive.is/hVrUH|archivedate=August 16, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Zealand">{{cite web|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2256|publisher=New Zealand Music Chart|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref> After less than five weeks, the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] certified the single [[Music certification|double-platinum]], denoting sales exceeding 30,000 units.<ref name="Recorded Music NZ">{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|accessdate=November 15, 2013|archivedate=November 15, 2013|archiveurl=http://archive.is/7a6n1|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart - 15 November 2013}}</ref> The song is listed as the 48th best-selling single of all time in New Zealand, making Perry the only singer to have the most entries, which including "[[California Gurls]]", "[[Firework (song)|Firework]]" and "[[E.T. (song)|E.T.]].<ref>[http://www.charts.org.nz/bestall.asp charts.org.nz. - New Zealand charts portal]. Best Of All Time list]. Retrieved on 6 January 2014.</ref> In Australia, the song debuted at number three on the [[ARIA Singles Chart]], before climbing to number one the following week; thus becoming Perry's third number one single in Australia.<ref name="ARIA">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry's ROAR Tops ARIA Singles Chart|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/41887/katy-perry%27s-roar-tops-aria-singles-chart?pos=0|publisher=ARIA Music News|accessdate=August 2013}}</ref> In less than a month, [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] certified the single two-times platinum, and as of October 2013, the song received a quadruple-platinum certification, denoting sales of 280,000 copies. As of December 2013, Roar has been certified 7x Platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and has sold 560,000 copies in Australia alone.<ref name="ariacharts.com.au">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=September 14, 2013|archiveurl=http://archive.is/iWHEe|archivedate=September 14, 2013|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles Chart - 16/09/2013}}</ref> "Roar" peaked at number two in the [[Record Report|Venezuelan Pop Rock Chart]].<ref name="Record Report - Pop Rock General">{{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6JFZnFQG2|title=Record Report - Pop Rock General|language=Spanish|url=http://www.recordreport.com.ve/publico/?i=poprock|date=August 31, 2013|archivedate=August 30, 2013|work=[[Record Report]]|publisher= R.R. Digital C.A. }}</ref><ref name="Record Report - Pop Rock General" /> On the [[Gaon Chart]] of South Korea, it reached number one on the international chart.<ref name="Gaon Digital Chart">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/digital_chart/index.php?nationGbn=E&current_year=&current_month=07&current_week=34&chart_Time=week|title=Gaon Digital Chart|date=August 17, 2013|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> In Japan, the song entered the [[Japan Hot 100]] at number seven.<ref name="Japan Hot 100">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305595/katy-perry/chart?f=848 |accessdate=August 2, 2013|title=Japan Hot 100 }}</ref> The reached number one in both the [[Media Forest]] airplay chart in Israel, and the [[The Official Lebanese Top 20|Lebanese Singles Chart]].<ref name="mediaforest.biz">{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaforest.biz/WeeklyCharts/HistoryWeeklyCharts.aspx?year=2013&week=35e|work = Midia Forest|accessdate=June 13, 2013|title=Israel International Chart - August 25, 2013 }}</ref><ref name="olt1">{{cite web|url=http://www.olt20.com/Katy-Perry#fragment-2 |title=The Official Lebanese Top 20 <U+2013> Katy Perry |publisher=Olt20.com |date= |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> Similarly, in [[South Africa]], the song peaked at number two on the [[Mediaguide]] airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web |title=South African Airplay Top 10 |work=[[Mediaguide]] |publisher=Entertainment Logistics Services |date=September 17, 2013 |url=http://www.sa-ema.com/index.php/charts-board/?keywords=2013-09-17|}}</ref>

In Russia, on the [[Russian Music Charts|Tophit Weekly General Airplay chart]] the song debuted at number 395 on August 25, 2013 and it has climbed the chart, peaking so far at number five on November 17, 2013.<ref name="tophitru.com">[http://www.tophitru.com/cgi-bin/trackinfo.cgi?id=50218 <U+041E><U+0441><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+043D><U+044B><U+0435> <U+043F><U+0430><U+0440><U+0430><U+043C><U+0435><U+0442><U+0440><U+044B> <U+0440><U+043E><U+0442><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+0438> <U+0442><U+0440><U+0435><U+043A><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0440><U+0430><U+0434><U+0438><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430><U+043D><U+0446><U+0438><U+044F><U+0445>, <U+0440><U+0430><U+0431><U+043E><U+0442><U+0430><U+044E><U+0449><U+0438><U+0445> <U+0432> <U+0441><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+043C><U+0435> TOPHIT.RU<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On the [[Russian Music Charts|Top Hit Weekly Audience Choice chart]], it peaked at number three on the issue dated October 27, 2013.<ref name="tophitru.com"/>

==Music video==
Filming of the official music video for "Roar" began on August 7, 2013 and ended on August 9, 2013. The video was released on September 5, 2013, directed by Grady Hall and Mark Kudsi, and filmed at the [[Los Angeles County Arboretum and Botanic Garden]].<ref name=":40">{{cite web|author=2 months ago |url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/news/41887/katy-perry%27s-roar-tops-aria-singles-chart?pos=0 |title=Katy Perry's ROAR Tops ARIA Singles Chart - ARIA Music News |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> A 21-second teaser of the video had previously been uploaded on August 25, 2013.<ref name="RoarTeaser">{{cite web|last=Perry|first=Katy|title=Roar: Queen of the Jungle (Music Video Preview)|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yD_-C7Hn2Y|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=August 25, 2013}}</ref> Nokia posted a two-minute [[Making-of|behind the scenes]] video on September 4, 2013.<ref name="BehindRoarScenes">{{cite web|title=Katy Perry "Roar" - Official Nokia Exclusive Behind the Scenes|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8UUSB9iKIy8|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=September 4, 2013}}</ref> On November 14, 2013, an extended 17-minute behind-the-scenes video was uploaded to Perry's official VEVO account.<ref>{{YouTube|Z0Q8j3HJagE|Katy Perry - Making of the "Roar" Music Video}}</ref>

===Synopsis===
The video begins with a scene showing Perry and her boyfriend having crashed their plane in the jungle. Perry shows signs of worry, while her boyfriend takes pictures of himself and dumps his bags on her to explore. As it turns to night, Perry and her boyfriend are still wandering through the jungle as her boyfriend throws things back at her. Suddenly, he is attacked by a tiger and Perry dumps her bags and runs off screaming. She approaches a lake and is almost bitten by a crocodile when she puts her hand in the water. She sits on a rock and ends up covered in tarantulas and [[Tachypnea|breathing rapidly]]. As Perry looks into the lake while singing the chorus, she sees a reflection of a tiger instead of herself. Behind her in the darkness there are dozens of pairs of blinking eyes, but they are revealed to be fireflies which fly around Perry before forming an image of a roaring tiger in the sky.

[[File:Katy Perry-Roar video.jpg|thumb|Perry in the music video for "Roar" dressed as "Queen of the Jungle".]] 
Presumably a few days later, Perry has since made friends with a monkey and uses her [[stiletto heel]] to form a spear. She uses it to shoot a banana, which she gives to the monkey. In another scene, Perry is bathing in the lake, with the help of an elephant who sprays her with water from the lake using its trunk. Perry helps a crocodile by brushing its teeth using a toothbrush she has salvaged, and tries to reach her clothes which have been taken by the elephant. At night, she holds a torch and explores a cave. Inside, she watches an animated drawing on the wall in which humans try to kill a tiger; attempting to burn it as it grows stronger and shooting spears which it sends firing back towards them. When she leaves the cave, it is light outside and Perry is wearing a leopard-print bra and [[grass skirt]], displaying a boost of confidence and holding the spear she made earlier. She stands on top of a waterfall, overlooking the jungle, and then swings across the sky on a [[vine]].

With the help of the monkey, Perry builds a cat toy which she uses to distract the tiger who ate her boyfriend earlier in the video. She lures it into an area of the jungle, and traps it inside. She comes face-to-face with the tiger and the two of them roar at each other, until Perry's roar [[Tame animal|tames]] the tiger as it sits in front of her submissively. Afterwards, Perry is shown sitting on a giant grass throne, wearing a flower crown as the rest of the jungle animals sit around her, including the tiger, monkey and elephant. The tiger is shown wearing a collar that says "Kitty Purry", a reference to Perry's real-life cat of the same name. Perry takes [[selfie]]s with the monkey on her boyfriend's phone, and applies lipstick made from berries she has picked. She also paints the elephant's toenails pink. Perry awakens from sleeping in the plane, leading the viewer to think all the previous events have just been a dream, but walks out of the plane still in the jungle, stretching her arms and yawning with the animals sitting around her.

===Reception===
Upon its release, the music video received mixed reviews from critics. [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] contributors Robbie Daw, Sam Lansky, and Carl Willott gave it mostly lackluster reviews. Daw considered that the release of such a "safe" video was a disappointment for Perry and expressed eagerness to her next single; while Lansky likened its "edg[iness]" to that of a "woman's antiperspirant commercial"; and the latter divided the video in what he considered to be of "good cheesy" and "bad cheesy": he highlighted the fake set, Perry's acting and the ending, but criticized the CGI, which he deemed "dopey", the product placement and Perry's "overly literal roar-off with a tiger". The only writer for the website that gave the visual a favorable review was Mike Wass, who appreciated the "campy element[s]" in it, while noting that it drew inspiration from the [[Doctor Jones#Music video|music video for "Doctor Jones"]] by the dance-pop group [[Aqua (band)|Aqua]]. In total, the reviews had an average score of approximately 6 out of 10.<ref>{{cite web|author=Wass, Mike|title=Pop Perspective: Katy Perry's "Roar" Video Reviewed By All Four Idolator Editors|url=http://www.idolator.com/7482925/pop-perspective-katy-perry-roar-video|work=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|publisher=Spin Media|accessdate=December 25, 2013|date=September 6, 2013}}</ref>

James Montgomery from [[MTV]] believed that the video drew inspiration from ''[[Sheena, Queen of the Jungle]]'' and stated the video did not take itself too seriously, describing it as "[[Camp (style)|camp]]".<ref name="mtvnews">{{cite web|last=Montgomery|first=James|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713557/katy-perry-roar-music-video-premiere.jhtml|title=Katy Perry's 'Roar' Video: All Hail The Queen Of The Jungle|publisher=[[MTV.com|MTV News]]|accessdate=September 14, 2013|date=September 5, 2013}}</ref> [[Slant Magazine]] writer Sal Cinquemani was neutral about the video, noting that although ''Prism'' was being billed as a departure for Perry, both "Roar" and its video were not.<ref>{{cite web|author=Cinquemani, Sal|title=Music Video: Katy Perry's "Roar"|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/house/2013/05/music-video-katy-perry-roar|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|accessdate=December 25, 2013|date=September 5, 2013}}</ref> Perry was criticized by [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] for using exotic animals in the video for "Roar". Merrilee Burke from PETA stated: "Animals used for entertainment endure horrific cruelty and suffer from extreme confinement and violent training methods." Burke also declared that the animals involved in the music video were allegedly provided by a company who was criticized by US officials.<ref name="peta">{{cite web|last=Lockley|first=Hannah|url=http://uk.omg.yahoo.com/news/katy-perry-criticised-peta-using-endangered-animals-roar-135440982.html|title=Katy Perry Criticized By Peta For Using Endangered Animals In Roar Video|publisher=Yahoo OMG! UK|accessdate=September 14, 2013|date=September 14, 2013}}</ref> Perry responded by obtaining a letter from the [[American Humane Association]], which had representatives present at the three-day shoot. It stated that "After reviewing the reports, we believe that the Guidelines for the Safe Use of Animals in Filmed Media were followed and that no animal was harmed in the making of this music video".<ref name="katypeta">{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Hillary|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/entertainment/katy-perry-responds-peta-criticism-animal-use-roar-video-4B11180867|title=Katy Perry responds to PETA criticism of animal use in 'Roar' video|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=October 5, 2013|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref>

==Live performances==
Perry first performed "Roar" at the [[2013 MTV Video Music Awards]], under the [[Brooklyn Bridge]], as the ceremony's closing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wickman|first=Kase|title=Katy Perry Makes Brooklyn 'Roar' With Epic VMA Finale|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1713031/katy-perry-roar-vma-finale.jhtml|website=[[MTV]]|publisher=[[Viacom]]|accessdate=December 1, 2013|date=August 26, 2013}}</ref> She performed the song on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on October 12, 2013.<ref name="snlarchives">{{cite web|url=http://snlarchives.net/detail.php?i=201310128|title=SNL Archives - Episodes - Details|work=The SNL Archives|last=Navaroli|first=Joel|accessdate=January 7, 2014}}</ref> While hosting ''We Can Survive: Music for Life'' on October 23, 2013, she performed the song with [[Sara Bareilles]], [[Bonnie McKee]], [[Ellie Goulding]], [[Kacey Musgraves]], and duo [[Tegan and Sara]].<ref name="Hollywood Bowl">{{cite web|last=Aguila|first=Justino|title=Katy Perry Hosts Famous Friends, Previews Next Tour at Hollywood Bowl: Live Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5770379/katy-perry-hosts-famous-friends-previews-next-tour-at-hollywood|publisher=''Billboard''|date=October 24, 2013}}</ref> She also performed the song at the Australian version of the ''X Factor'' on October 28, 2013.<ref name=XFactorPrismSongs>{{cite web|last=Kevipod|first=Kevin|title=Katy Perry Performs "Roar" & "Unconditionally" on "The X Factor Australia"|url=http://www.directlyrics.com/katy-perry-performs-roar-uncoditionally-on-the-x-factor-australia-news.html|publisher=directlyrics.com|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref> Perry performed the song on German TV show ''[[Schlag den Raab]]'' on November 16, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schlag den Raab 43 vom 16. November 2013|url=http://www.prosieben.de/tv/schlag-den-raab/episodenguide/143-schlag-den-raab-43-vom-16-november-2013|publisher=ProSiebenSat1 Networld|author=ProSieben|date=November 16, 2013}}</ref> On December 14, 2013, Perry performed "Roar" at the [[NRJ Music Awards]], but suffered technical difficulties which resulted in her performance being stopped by the host halfway through who asked for it to be restarted. This led many to believe that Perry had initially been lip-syncing the performance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katy Perry accused of lip-syncing "Roar" at NRJ Music Awards|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/katy-perry-accused-of-lipsynching-roar-at-the-nrj-music-awards-in-france/story-e6frfn09-1226785867582|publisher=News.com.au|accessdate=January 21, 2014}}</ref> NRJ later released an apology to Perry, stating that she had been singing live but that the wrong mix of the song was played over her live vocals, which resulted in her being visually out of sync with the backing track.<ref name="nrj">{{cite web|url=http://nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr/nomines-4519/artiste/actu/561-katy-perry.html?actu_id=306298_katy-perry-remporte-le-nrj-music-award-du-best-digital-moment-|title=KATY PERRY REMPORTE LE NRJ MUSIC AWARD DU BEST DIGITAL MOMENT !|language=French|last=|first=|publisher=nrjmusicawards.nrj.fr|date=December 15, 2013 |accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref>

